BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:UC Love Data Week 2026 (February 9-13)
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260212T180000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260213T010000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51959615323410
DESCRIPTION:UC Love Data Week (UCLDW) is a week-long offering of presentat
 ions and workshops from across the University of California focused on all
  things data. All members of the UC community are welcome to attend this f
 ree\, virtual event. \n\n \n\n\n\n\n\nSee the full schedule by day and reg
 ister now.\n\n \n\nWith over 20 presentations and workshops\, whether you
 ’re working with qualitative or quantitative data\, there’s plenty to 
 choose from. This year's topics include: \n\n\n\nData visualizationIntegra
 ting AIWorking with data in R and PythonData repositoriesand much more!\n\
 n \n\nWorkshops taught during UCLDW by UC Davis DataLab and Librarians inc
 lude:\n\n\n\nMonday\, 2/9 at 11 AM - Intro to OpenRefine for Data Cleaning
 Monday\, 2/9 at 2 PM - How to Use Data Repository FindersWednesday\, 2/11 
 at 10 AM - How I Slacked at Work and Accidentally Built an Automated\, AI 
 Driven ETL PipelineThursday\, 2/12 at 10 AM - Visualizing data with ggplot
  for R users (offered in person at DataLab and via Zoom!)\n\n \n\nFor more
  information please visit the UC Love Data Week website.  Please register 
 with your UC campus email. Zoom links will be emailed to registered partic
 ipants.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/uc-love-data-week-2026-februa
 ry-9-13
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Workshop: Visualizing data with ggplot for R users
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260212T180000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260212T200000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51818215462712
DESCRIPTION:If a picture tells a thousand words then a data visualization 
 can convey a million! Join us to learn how to apply data visualization pri
 nciples and best practices to generate compelling plots with ggplot in R. 
 Through a series of case studies\, we'll make static plots and practice it
 erating to improve upon them and the data stories they tell.\n\nThis works
 hop is for current R users who want to expand their plotting skills\, and 
 thus is not an introduction to the R programming langauge. It is part of D
 ataLab's "Intermediate R" training series\, which you can learn more about
  on our training website.\n\n \n\nAfter completing this workshop\, learner
 s should be able to:\n\n* write code to generate plots in R using the ggpl
 ot2 package\n\n* develop various different plot types (dot plots\, histogr
 ams\, bar charts\, boxplots\, time series\, etc.)\n\n* employ ggplot's gra
 mmar of graphics syntax to customize plots\,\n\n* effectively use layers a
 nd aesthetics to make plots more informative and meaningful (including add
 ing groupings\, scaling\, color\, faceting\, labels\, and trendlines)\n\n 
 \n\nThis workshop is offered in person and as a virtual broadcast as part 
 of UC Love Data Week. Local learners are encouraged to attend in person. A
 ll members of the University of California system are welcome to register.
  Advance registration required.\n\n \n\n \n\nPrerequisites\n\nThis worksho
 p is intended for motivated learners from all domains at UC Davis and the 
 other UCs who want to hone their existing R skills. Thus\, we won't cover 
 introductory R questions during this session. Participants should be comfo
 rtable with basic R syntax\, and have the latest version of R and RStudio 
 pre-installed and running on their laptops. If you're new to R\, or want t
 o brush up\, we suggest you start with our "R Basics" workshop curriculum.
 \n\n \n\nCan’t attend this event? Materials from prior UC Davis DataLab 
 workshops are available on DataLab's website. Check out our workshop sched
 ule for other upcoming trainings.\n\n \n\nQuestions? Contact datalab-train
 ing@ucdavis.edu.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/workshop-w2026-intermediate-r
 -ggplot
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
