SUMMARY:Covered: Faculty Author Talks by Emily Klancher Merchant\, Talinn 
 Grigor & Houri Berberian
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260311T003000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260311T023000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51817231960329
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an evening with UC Davis faculty authors Emily Kla
 ncher Merchant and Talinn Grigor\, and UC Irvine faculty author Houri Berb
 erian as part of Covered\, a monthly event series celebrating recent books
  from the College of Letters and Science.\n \n\nEmily Klancher Merchant\, 
 associate professor of Science and Technology Studies\, discusses DNA\, Ra
 ce\, and Reproduction\, an interdisciplinary volume exploring how genomic 
 ideas shape racial identity and reproductive decision-making.\n Talinn Gri
 gor\, professor of art history\, and Houri Berberian\, professor of histor
 y and director of the Center for Armenian Studies at UC Irvine\, share ins
 ights from The Armenian Woman\, which traces Armenian women’s cultural\,
  political and intellectual influence on Iranian modernity.  \n\n\n\n\nCov
 ered: Spotlighting Faculty Authors in Letters and Science is co-sponsored 
 by the Jan Shrem and Maria Manetti Shrem Museum and the UC Davis Library.
LOCATION:Manetti Shrem Museum
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/covered-faculty-author-talks-
 march2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Introduction to Remote Computing and HPC (2-day workshop)
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260317
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260317
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51809290267949
DESCRIPTION:Are you working on a research project but finding that your da
 ta is too big for your laptop\, or that your code must run for a long time
 ? You need more compute power!\n \n\nThis 2-day intensive workshop provide
 s an introduction to accessing and computing on remote servers such as UC 
 Davis’ HPC (high performance cluster) to elevate your research. \n \n\nT
 he series covers everything you need to know to get started. We’ll provi
 de an overview of HPC terminology\, architecture\, and general workflows\,
  and guide learners through how to set up and use SSH to log in and transf
 er files\, how to install software with miniconda\, how to reserve computi
 ng time and run programs with SLURM\, and execute shell commands that are 
 especially useful for working with servers. As we learn we’ll practice a
 ccessing and computing on remote servers using the UC Davis HPC Core Facil
 ity’s new “Hive” cluster.\n \n\nThe material builds and thus learner
 s must attend both days. Sessions run from 10 AM - 4 PM each day\, with a 
 break for lunch.\n \n\nAfter this workshop series\, learners should be abl
 e to:\n\nUse SSH to log in to a server\;Transfer files to and from a serve
 r\;Set up and use conda/mamba to install software on a server\;Use SLURM t
 o run interactive and non-interactive software on a server\;Explain etique
 tte for using a server cluster such as Hive.\nThis workshop is subject to 
 cancellation if minimum enrollment is not achieved.\n \n\nPREREQUISITES\n\
 nParticipants should have taken DataLab’s “Introduction to the Unix Co
 mmand Line” workshop\, or have equivalent prior experience using command
  line. Specifically\, you will need to know how to use command line to nav
 igate your file system and inspect\, create\, edit and move files. Partici
 pants must be comfortable with programming in a language such as R or Pyth
 on\, and with basic Linux shell syntax (i.e.\, able to navigate and create
 \, modify and move files via command line).\n \n\nLearners will register f
 or a HPC account during the session. CAS authentication is required.\n\n\n
 Can't make it to this training? Check out our workshop schedule. Materials
  from prior workshops are available on DataLab's website.\n \n\nQuestions?
  Email datalab-training@ucdavis.edu.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/introduction-to-remote-comput
 ing-and-hpc-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Davis R Users' Group
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260317T170000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260317T190000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51754758577096
DESCRIPTION:D-RUG\, our local R Users' Group\, meets weekly to facilitate 
 learning and using the R software language. R users from all domains are i
 nvited to bring their R-specific coding problems and share their experienc
 e with other members of the community. Meetup formats include everything f
 rom group discussion and mini-workshops to coworking sessions. D-RUG is ru
 n by volunteer Coo[R]dinators including UC Davis data scientists and gradu
 ate students dedicated to growing and strengthening the R community.\n\n \
 n\nToday's session is open-forum format to foster a communal\, co-working 
 environment. Come hang out and chat\, work on your own\, seek and give hel
 p\, and make friends.\n\n \n\nD-RUG meets Thursdays in person from 10 AM t
 o 12 PM at the DataLab Classroom (Shields Library room 360) on the UC Davi
 s campus. \n\nSign up for our mailing list to get the most up to date info
 rmation\, including a Zoom link to join us virtually if you can't make it 
 in person. Learn more about D-RUG on our website.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/davis-r-users-group-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
